"Reddy M.S., Boucher O.","Climate impact of black carbon emitted from energy consumption in the world's regions",2007,"Geophysical Research Letters","34","11", L11802,"","",,,10.1029/2006GL028904,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34547991101&partnerID=40&md5=f30f65df5c13aa57673fe12d8e35e2df","Met Office Hadley Centre, FitzRoy Road, Exeter EX1 3PB, United Kingdom; Laboratoire d'Optique Atmosphérique, CNRS, Université des Sciences et Technologies de Lille, Villeneuve d'Ascq, France","Reddy, M.S., Met Office Hadley Centre, FitzRoy Road, Exeter EX1 3PB, United Kingdom, Laboratoire d'Optique Atmosphérique, CNRS, Université des Sciences et Technologies de Lille, Villeneuve d'Ascq, France; Boucher, O., Met Office Hadley Centre, FitzRoy Road, Exeter EX1 3PB, United Kingdom, Laboratoire d'Optique Atmosphérique, CNRS, Université des Sciences et Technologies de Lille, Villeneuve d'Ascq, France","We have used the Laboratoire de Météorologie Dynamique General Circulation Model (LMD GCM) to estimate the contribution of different regions to global black carbon (BC) atmospheric burden and direct radiative forcing (DRF). On the global scale, fossil fuels and biofuels account for 66% and 34% of energy-related BC emissions, respectively. East and South Asia together contribute more than 50% of the global surface, atmospheric, and top-of-atmosphere DRF by BC. The regional contributions to global mean forcings closely follow the respective contributions to atmospheric burden. The global warming potential (GWP) of BC for different regions ranges from 374 to 677 with a global mean of 480. Europe is the largest contributor (63%) to BC deposition at high latitudes. The indirect GWP due to the BC effect on snow albedo is estimated to be largest for Europe (possibly as large as 1200), suggesting that BC emission reductions from this region are more efficient to mitigate climate change.",,"Atmospheric radiation; Carbon black; Computer simulation; Gas emissions; Global warming; Particulate emissions; Direct radiative forcing; General circulation model; Atmospheric aerosols; black carbon; carbon emission; climate change; climate effect; climate forcing; deposition; general circulation model; global warming; radiative forcing; Eurasia; Europe",,,,,,"Berntsen, B., Abatement of greenhouse gases: Does location matter? (2006) Clim. Impacts, 74, pp. 377-411; Bond, T.C., Sun, H.L., Can reducing black carbon emissions counteract global warming? (2005) Environ. Sci. Technol, 39, pp. 5921-5926; Bond, T.C., Streets, D.G., Yarber, K.F., Nelson, S.M., Woo, J.-H., Klimont, Z., A technology-based global inventory of black and organic carbon emissions from combustion (2004) J. Geophys. Res, 109, pp. D14203. , doi:10.1029/2003JD003697; Hansen, J., Nazarenko, L., Soot climate forcing via snow and ice albedos (2004) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U. S. A, 101, pp. 423-428; Hansen, J., Efficacy of climate forcings (2005) J. Geaphys. Res, 110, pp. D18104. , doi:10.1029/2005JD005776; Jacobson, M.Z., Global direct radiative forcing due to multicomponent anthropogenic and natural aerosols (2001) J. Geophys. Res, 106, pp. 1551-1568; Jacobson, M.Z., Climate response of fossil fuel and biofuel soot, accounting for soot's feedback to snow and sea ice albedo and emissivity (2004) J. Geophys. Res, 109, pp. D21201. , doi:10.1029/ 2004JD004945; Lohmann, U., Feichter, J., Can the direct and semi-direct aerosol effect compete with the indirect effect on a global scale? (2001) Geophys. Res. Lett, 28, pp. 159-161; Ramaswamy, V., et al. (2001), Radiative forcing of climate change, in Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis, Contribution of Working Group I to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, edited by J. T. Houghton et al., pp. 349-416, Cambridge Univ. Press, New YorkReddy, M.S., Boucher, O., A study of the global cycle of carbonaceous aerosols in the LMDZT general circulation model (2004) J. Geophys. Res, 109, pp. D14202. , doi:10.1029/